  <h1>How Divorce Asset Division Works</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Marital vs. separate property</h2><p>The first step in asset division is classifying property as marital (subject to division) or separate (not subject to division). Marital property: acquired during the marriage with marital funds. Separate property: owned before the marriage, received as a gift or inheritance during the marriage, or kept genuinely separate throughout. Commingling (mixing separate and marital funds) can convert separate property to marital property.</p>
  <h2>Community property states</h2><p>Arizona, California, Idaho, Louisiana, Nevada, New Mexico, Texas, Washington, and Wisconsin. All marital property is presumed 50/50 regardless of which spouse earned it. Courts have limited discretion to deviate. Prenuptial or postnuptial agreements can override the default.</p>
  <h2>Equitable distribution states</h2><p>All other states. Courts consider: length of marriage, each spouse&rsquo;s income and earning capacity, contributions to the marital estate (including homemaking), standard of living, age and health, and in some states, fault. Outcomes typically range from 45/55 to 60/40 depending on these factors.</p>
  <h2>Retirement accounts</h2><p>The portion of any retirement account (401(k), pension, IRA) accrued during the marriage is marital property. Division requires a Qualified Domestic Relations Order (QDRO) for employer-sponsored plans. IRAs use a transfer incident to divorce (no QDRO needed, but specific procedures apply). Failure to properly divide retirement accounts can result in taxes, penalties, and losing the awarded share.</p>
  <h2>Real estate</h2><p>The marital home is often the largest single asset. Options: sell and split equity; one spouse buys out the other&rsquo;s equity; defer sale until children finish school (with detailed co-ownership agreement). The buying spouse must qualify for a solo mortgage &mdash; courts cannot force a bank to lend.</p>
